explanation: To determine whether the conditional block in OS_mkfs is dead code you must know whether OS_FileSys_Initialize can ever return the legacy error codes and whether those legacy codes differ from the mapped code. 1) OS_FileSys_Initialize - required to inspect its implementation/contract and determine the set of possible return values and side-effects; if it never returns OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE or OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS the conditional body is unreachable at runtime (and therefore dead). Also needed to verify whether returning those values is deterministic, dependent on configuration, or produced only in tests/stubs. 2) OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE - the if-condition checks for this constant; you must know its definition/value and semantic meaning to tell if OS_FileSys_Initialize can yield it (and whether it is distinct from OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE). 3) OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS - same reason as above for the second compared constant. 4) OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE - the code maps the legacy errors to this value; you must know its definition/value to determine whether the assignment actually changes the return value (if values are identical the assignment is redundant and thus dead) and whether other code might rely on the normalized value. Together these symbols let you decide if the assignment/conditional can be executed and whether removing it would alter program behaviour (the definition of dead code per MISRA).
